00:03:50.480 --> 00:03:54.470
and "Atypical," which
focuses on an 18-year-old man

00:03:54.470 --> 00:03:58.310
on the autism spectrum trying
to find love on Netflix.

00:03:58.310 --> 00:04:00.200
In addition to that,
I hosted a TV show

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:02.690
called "The Different Is
Beautiful Show" for over two

00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:09.220
years with the theme that normal
is truly just a dryer setting.

00:04:09.220 --> 00:04:10.220
That was the main theme.

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:13.190
We brought in many people
impacted by diagnosis

00:04:13.190 --> 00:04:15.410
to share their stories
with the world to hear.

00:04:15.410 --> 00:04:17.000
And then, finally,
a nonprofit founder

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:18.560
who's had the wonderful--

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:20.510
I've had a wonderful
opportunity to give out

00:04:20.510 --> 00:04:23.030
52 scholarships for
students with autism

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:26.400
to go to college in
the past six years.

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:30.770
So in addition to that, in
addition to those two books,

00:04:30.770 --> 00:04:32.600
we were actually also
able to contribute

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:35.179
to another book called
"College for Students

00:04:35.179 --> 00:04:35.970
with Disabilities--

00:04:35.970 --> 00:04:40.070
We Do Belong," which focuses
on 17 stories of people

00:04:40.070 --> 00:04:44.300
with disabilities who
successfully navigated pursuing

00:04:44.300 --> 00:04:46.760
a post-secondary education.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:49.700
So some of the things you need
to know about our community

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:53.955
today is that, in terms
of the disabled community,

00:04:53.955 --> 00:04:56.330
we are the fastest growing
minority in the United States.

00:04:56.330 --> 00:05:00.675
One in five Americans currently
today has a disability.

00:05:00.675 --> 00:05:02.300
And we've had the
wonderful opportunity

00:05:02.300 --> 00:05:04.790
to work with
countless individuals

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:07.310
doing coaching, mentoring,
and training services

00:05:07.310 --> 00:05:09.350
for individuals
with special needs

00:05:09.350 --> 00:05:10.880
as they transition to adulthood.

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:13.250
And one of the big topics
we talk about, simply

00:05:13.250 --> 00:05:15.710
because of that, is employment.

00:05:15.710 --> 00:05:17.420
This has given us
opportunity to work

00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:20.240
with the Department
of Labor many times

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:23.960
on initiatives, such as the
Employer Assistant and Resource

00:05:23.960 --> 00:05:25.980
Network on disability inclusion.

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:28.250
It's a mouthful, so
we call it EARN, which

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:30.470
helps employers
recruit, hire, retain,

00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:32.819
and advance people
with disabilities.

00:05:32.819 --> 00:05:35.360
One of the big things you need
to know about the unemployment

00:05:35.360 --> 00:05:37.940
rate, unfortunately, for
those with disabilities today

00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:42.900
is that people with disabilities
are, for the most part,

00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:44.330
majorly unemployed.

00:05:44.330 --> 00:05:47.180
I mean, the autism community
is one of the biggest signs,

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:49.910
but in terms of the
overall rate of individuals

00:05:49.910 --> 00:05:52.280
with disabilities,
is just about 8.4%,

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:56.190
while people with
disabilities is 3.7%.

00:05:56.190 --> 00:05:58.310
So when we go into
businesses, we've

00:05:58.310 --> 00:06:01.520
had the wonderful opportunity to
work with some amazing, amazing

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:02.730
organizations.

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:05.810
We talk about these
main topics, but we talk

00:06:05.810 --> 00:06:07.459
about so much more as well.

00:06:07.459 --> 00:06:09.250
And one of the biggest
things we talk about

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:11.180
is that individuals
with disabilities

00:06:11.180 --> 00:06:14.300
are more likely to
stay at a job longer,

00:06:14.300 --> 00:06:18.290
reducing employee turnover.

00:06:18.290 --> 00:06:21.590
This has been a study
that's been done almost

00:06:21.590 --> 00:06:23.900
on an annual basis by the
Department of Labor that's

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:25.940
showing that people
with disabilities

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:29.120
are more committed to
staying at a company longer.

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:32.480
They're also, because
of the gratefulness

00:06:32.480 --> 00:06:37.490
of having meaningful employment,
having lower absentee rates.

00:06:37.490 --> 00:06:41.780
And in an environment
today where we're currently

00:06:41.780 --> 00:06:45.530
so focused on philanthropy
in many of our businesses,

00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:49.190
87% customers say
they prefer shopping

00:06:49.190 --> 00:06:53.060
at stores and with companies
that hire employees

00:06:53.060 --> 00:06:55.220
with disabilities.

00:06:55.220 --> 00:06:57.110
And higher company
standing once,

00:06:57.110 --> 00:07:00.530
if an employee leaves because of
the diversity that was offered,

00:07:00.530 --> 00:07:04.160
they're more likely to
go onto any recruiter

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:07.850
websites and encourage
people to follow

00:07:07.850 --> 00:07:10.580
that company because
of them hiring people

00:07:10.580 --> 00:07:11.910
with disabilities.

00:07:11.910 --> 00:07:15.006
And then finally, in terms
of reasonable accommodations

00:07:15.006 --> 00:07:17.630
today, one of the biggest things
I get when I go into companies

00:07:17.630 --> 00:07:19.970
is, how much will the
bottom line cost me

00:07:19.970 --> 00:07:22.220
for hiring someone
with a disability based

00:07:22.220 --> 00:07:23.900
on reasonable accommodations?

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:25.590
And I'm glad to
say today, and it's

00:07:25.590 --> 00:07:28.790
something I spread so much
awareness about year-round,

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:31.490
is that's more than
half of accommodations

00:07:31.490 --> 00:07:35.480
today are absolutely
free, which does nothing

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:36.540
to the bottom line.

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:38.130
So it's a nice
little perk there.

00:07:38.130 --> 00:07:39.630
Just to give you a
little background

00:07:39.630 --> 00:07:42.020
