and how we could
go into businesses

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:19.630
and talk about hosting
sensory-friendly events

00:12:19.630 --> 00:12:22.870
for maybe people who
are adults with autism

00:12:22.870 --> 00:12:25.840
or other disabilities, to
make sure that they feel

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:27.520
included in the workplace.

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:30.400
We've talked to
many land developers

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:33.610
about things such as
the lights in some rooms

00:12:33.610 --> 00:12:35.620
and how some individuals
with disabilities

00:12:35.620 --> 00:12:37.450
might have things
such as sensory issues

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:41.980
where bright lights might cause
them a little bit of issues,

00:12:41.980 --> 00:12:45.040
to even talking about
the size of walls,

00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:49.270
to make environments a little
less loud for individuals

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:50.980
with special needs as well.

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:53.210
So we've started
talking about that

00:12:53.210 --> 00:12:56.320
via a nonprofit organization
we started in 2011

00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:57.970
called KFM Making a Difference.

00:12:57.970 --> 00:13:01.240
At the same time, I was
pursuing my first year

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:02.470
as a professional speaker.

00:13:02.470 --> 00:13:04.960
So now we go around to
countless businesses

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:08.950
and talk about the need
for more sensory-friendly

00:13:08.950 --> 00:13:11.537
actual environments for
individuals with disabilities.

00:13:11.537 --> 00:13:13.870
In addition to that, we've
had the wonderful opportunity

00:13:13.870 --> 00:13:17.530
to give out a scholarship
for students with autism

00:13:17.530 --> 00:13:19.450
to pursue a
post-secondary education,

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:22.060
where we now are able to
say that we've given out

00:13:22.060 --> 00:13:24.670
over 52 scholarships
for students with autism

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:28.930
across the United States and
internationally to pursue

00:13:28.930 --> 00:13:32.170
a post-secondary education.

00:13:32.170 --> 00:13:35.290
And in addition to that,
the other big reason

00:13:35.290 --> 00:13:37.630
why we do what we do
today is because we

00:13:37.630 --> 00:13:40.300
understand that autism
and disability is

00:13:40.300 --> 00:13:43.240
a life-long disorder.

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:45.820
So each one of
these individuals--

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:47.950
when I was growing up,
I had no peer mentoring.

00:13:47.950 --> 00:13:50.890
And now I go into businesses
and I talk to them

00:13:50.890 --> 00:13:53.761
about the importance of
peer mentors for anyone,

00:13:53.761 --> 00:13:55.510
regardless if you're
just starting the job

00:13:55.510 --> 00:13:57.610
or regardless if
you're non-disabled

00:13:57.610 --> 00:13:59.920
because each and
every single one of us

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:01.770
need to think about
self-reflection at times

00:14:01.770 --> 00:14:04.790
and what's going to be our
potential in the future.

00:14:04.790 --> 00:14:06.740
It's so very, very important.

00:14:06.740 --> 00:14:08.410
So I want to share
a story with you.

00:14:08.410 --> 00:14:10.180
So over three years
ago, we started

00:14:10.180 --> 00:14:14.170
a Facebook page called A Special
Community, where we highlight

00:14:14.170 --> 00:14:16.480
people impacted by a diagnosis.

00:14:16.480 --> 00:14:20.680
We now have over 120,000
Facebook followers, all

00:14:20.680 --> 00:14:25.060
comprised of amazing, amazing
people from our community.

00:14:25.060 --> 00:14:27.990
And every single
place we go speak

00:14:27.990 --> 00:14:30.010
now, we bring a
tripod and a camera

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:33.050
and we highlight people
impacted by a diagnosis

00:14:33.050 --> 00:14:35.560
to share their stories
with the world.

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:39.610
But we also start out each
interview with one question.

00:14:39.610 --> 00:14:42.160
And it's, what would
you like for the world

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:43.780
to know about you?

00:14:43.780 --> 00:14:45.880
And we met this
amazing kid named Liam.

00:14:45.880 --> 00:14:47.720
He's 10 years old
from Minnesota.

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:51.310
And he said he wanted people
to know that sometimes,

00:14:51.310 --> 00:14:53.980
because of autism,
it's sometimes

00:14:53.980 --> 00:14:55.930
difficult to make friends.

00:14:55.930 --> 00:14:58.684
And I wanted to share with you
his story really quickly today.

00:14:58.684 --> 00:14:59.350
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:14:59.350 --> 00:15:01.280
- So we're going to be
talking to the camera

00:15:01.280 --> 00:15:03.380
and we want to make you famous.

00:15:03.380 --> 00:15:08.470
So we literally want to make you
probably the most famous person

00:15:08.470 --> 00:15:09.160
on the planet.

00:15:09.160 --> 00:15:10.900
How's that sound?

00:15:10.900 --> 00:15:13.543
- OK, OK.

00:15:13.543 --> 00:15:14.505
- No pressure.

00:15:14.505 --> 00:15:18.225
- Autism basically makes
it hard to connect.

00:15:18.225 --> 00:15:22.680
It makes it hard to get that
connection, to make friends.

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:30.150
They feel like more loners
than, well, in groups.

00:15:30.150 --> 00:15:32.745
It's also a learning disability.

00:15:32.745 --> 00:15:35.320
And in some cases, it's hard--

00:15:38.860 --> 00:15:41.640
you can't speak in some cases.

00:15:41.640 --> 00:15:45.470
I met a kid called
Tom, who he has autism,

00:15:45.470 --> 00:15:48.260
but he can't speak
in proper English.

00:15:48.260 --> 00:15:50.340
He needs an iPad.

00:15:50.340 --> 00:15:51.930
- So Liam, one
thing I want to know

00:15:51.930 --> 00:15:55.690
is that I was actually diagnosed
with autism at an early age,

00:15:55.690 --> 00:15:56.190
too.

00:15:56.190 --> 00:15:58.398
And I don't know if I've
ever actually told you that.

00:15:58.398 --> 00:16:01.410
But I want you to know
that I will always

00:16:01.410 --> 00:16:04.160
be here to be your friend,
if you need a friend.

00:16:04.160 --> 00:16:05.221
OK?

00:16:05.221 --> 00:16:05.720
- Yeah.

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:08.920
- Because even though
it may be hard at times

00:16:08.920 --> 00:16:12.840
to connect to other
people, I feel

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:15.720
like so many people
with autism like us just

00:16:15.720 --> 00:16:20.200
want what anyone else
wants, to feel connected

00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:21.390
and to have a friend.

00:16:21.390 --> 00:16:23.976
So you've always got
a friend in me, OK?

00:16:23.976 --> 00:16:25.490
Want to pound this out?

00:16:25.490 --> 00:16:26.060
- Yeah.

00:16:26.060 --> 00:16:27.509
Can you blow it up, too?

00:16:27.509 --> 00:16:30.890
Oh, he blows it up.

00:16:30.890 --> 00:16:32.339
You're awesome, Liam.

00:16:32.339 --> 00:16:35.664
- I'm kind of tearing up.

00:16:35.664 --> 00:16:36.164
Sorry.

00:16:36.164 --> 00:16:37.140
- That's OK.

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:38.116
It's kind of emotional.

00:16:38.116 --> 00:16:38.885
[END PLAYBACK]

00:16:38.885 --> 00:16:41.010
KERRY MAGRO: So we've had
the wonderful opportunity

00:16:41.010 --> 00:16:42.840
to meet with hundreds
and hundreds of kids

00:16:42.840 --> 00:16:46.860
around the world, to
hear their stories.

00:16:46.860 --> 00:16:48.690
But then we took a step forward.

00:16:48.690 --> 00:16:50.610
After every single
video we've done,

00:16:50.610 --> 00:16:52.230
we've done a
self-assessment to see

00:16:52.230 --> 00:16:56.250
how we can go about
helping maximize anything

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:57.397
they mention in the video.

00:16:57.397 --> 00:16:58.980
So one of the biggest
things with Liam

00:16:58.980 --> 00:17:00.820
was he wanted to make friends.

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:02.666
So after that video
went viral on Facebook,

00:17:02.666 --> 00:17:05.040
we started a Facebook group
for him called Liam's Buddies

00:17:05.040 --> 00:17:07.079
where, moderated by
his mom, we would

00:17:07.079 --> 00:17:09.599
have countless people
just saying that they

00:17:09.599 --> 00:17:11.089
wanted to be Liam's friend.

00:17:11.089 --> 00:17:13.770
That gave Liam the
courage to actually want

00:17:13.770 --> 00:17:16.290
to pursue trying to make
more friends at his school.

00:17:16.290 --> 00:17:19.200
And now I can say that he
has two really close friends

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:20.790
at his school today.

00:17:20.790 --> 00:17:23.970
So we took this idea to start
just doing more and more

00:17:23.970 --> 00:17:28.710
interviews, and this gave us an
idea to focus on how we can do

00:17:28.710 --> 00:17:32.850
this to maximize employers'
understanding the world about

00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:36.150
people with disabilities
and what they would like

00:17:36.150 --> 00:17:37.350
for companies to know.

00:17:37.350 --> 00:17:39.090
We've actually
started a video series

00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:41.130
to highlight people
with disabilities.

00:17:41.130 --> 00:17:44.790
To every single place we go,
we try to share at least one

00:17:44.790 --> 00:17:47.190
or two videos for people
to get the perspectives

00:17:47.190 --> 00:17:49.080
of individuals, not
only with autism,

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:52.050
but a wide range
of disabilities.

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:55.860
So the individual right
here, his name is David.

00:17:55.860 --> 00:18:00.510
And David is actually one of the
most amazing people I've ever

00:18:00.510 --> 00:18:01.470
met in my entire life.

00:18:01.470 --> 00:18:02.910
David is blind.

00:18:02.910 --> 00:18:07.530
He has a very rare disease
where he actually went blind

00:18:07.530 --> 00:18:08.970
at a very, very early age.

00:18:08.970 --> 00:18:11.850
And during his accommodations
when he was growing up,

00:18:11.850 --> 00:18:15.420
he had to learn how to use
a walking cane to get around

00:18:15.420 --> 00:18:18.930
and he had to navigate
reasonable accommodations

00:18:18.930 --> 00:18:20.970
once he transitioned
to adulthood.

00:18:20.970 --> 00:18:25.230
And now, actually, today we met
him speaking at a Work Matters

00:18:25.230 --> 00:18:28.620
summit at PNC Bank in
Pennsylvania, where

00:18:28.620 --> 00:18:31.560
we tried to talk about
the ROI benefits of hiring

00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:32.890
people with disabilities.

00:18:32.890 --> 00:18:35.246
And this is what David wanted
to share with the world.

00:18:35.246 --> 00:18:35.912
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:18:35.912 --> 00:18:40.340
- The greatest
challenge was being

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:45.030
afraid to admit that
I was going blind.

00:18:45.030 --> 00:18:51.400
I was afraid to use a white
cane to travel independently.

00:18:51.400 --> 00:18:55.810
And I did, you know--

00:18:55.810 --> 00:18:57.640
and then once you
face your fears,

00:18:57.640 --> 00:19:01.950
and you learn the skills,
strategies, and techniques

00:19:01.950 --> 00:19:04.199
as well as a
positive philosophy,

00:19:04.199 --> 00:19:06.594
understanding and
believing that it's

00:19:06.594 --> 00:19:08.510
respectable to
have a disability,

00:19:08.510 --> 00:19:11.384
and surrounding yourself
with other people who

00:19:11.384 --> 00:19:15.175
are possibility thinkers,
and say, hey, I can do it.

00:19:15.175 --> 00:19:16.365
You can, too.

00:19:16.365 --> 00:19:22.540
And I think that's
one of the things

00:19:22.540 --> 00:19:26.450
that I had to really
come to grips with.

00:19:26.450 --> 00:19:29.970
And then once I
learned, once I really

00:19:29.970 --> 00:19:33.463
believed that it was respectable
to have a disability, once I

00:19:33.463 --> 00:19:35.459
learned to use
assistive technology,

00:19:35.459 --> 00:19:38.952
once I learned to use a cane
to travel independently,

00:19:38.952 --> 00:19:43.443
once I recognized and
embraced those things,

00:19:43.443 --> 00:19:45.460
life got a whole lot better.

00:19:45.460 --> 00:19:49.270
Privileged, Kerry, to serve
as the executive director

00:19:49.270 --> 00:19:51.490
of the Department of
Labor and Industry's

00:19:51.490 --> 00:19:53.815
Office of Vocation
and Rehabilitation.

00:19:53.815 --> 00:19:57.875
And we're the lead agency
responsible for employment

00:19:57.875 --> 00:20:01.500
and training for people with
disabilities in Pennsylvania.

00:20:01.500 --> 00:20:03.570
We've worked with
over 70,000 people

00:20:03.570 --> 00:20:08.350
and helped over 8,500
people with disabilities

00:20:08.350 --> 00:20:10.630
find real jobs with real pay.

00:20:10.630 --> 00:20:16.940
So we're here today to partner
with PNC and other community

00:20:16.940 --> 00:20:20.190
advocates and partners
to shine a positive light

00:20:20.190 --> 00:20:23.360
on the potential of
individuals with disabilities

00:20:23.360 --> 00:20:25.322
and to help people
recognize and understand

00:20:25.322 --> 00:20:27.030
and believe that people
with disabilities

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:30.550
are the most untapped talent
pool for employers to consider.

00:20:30.550 --> 00:20:34.240
So that's why we're here is
to help spread the good word.

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:41.960
And [INAUDIBLE] don't confuse
a bad day with a bad life.

00:20:44.690 --> 00:20:47.210
And I think that's--

00:20:47.210 --> 00:20:50.890
everybody has bad days.

00:20:50.890 --> 00:20:51.860
Everybody gets upset.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:00.530
But I think that's really it.

00:21:00.530 --> 00:21:02.580
You've got to-- don't
just go through it

00:21:02.580 --> 00:21:04.920
you've got to grow through it.

00:21:04.920 --> 00:21:05.760
Sorry.

00:21:05.760 --> 00:21:08.360
So I think that's
really important.

00:21:08.360 --> 00:21:10.370
Don't confuse a bad
day with a bad life.

00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:12.390
That's really, really important.

00:21:12.390 --> 00:21:14.705
There's going to be good
days, there's going to be ups,

00:21:14.705 --> 00:21:16.200
there's going to be downs.

00:21:16.200 --> 00:21:19.320
Some days you're the statue and
some days you're the pigeon.

00:21:19.320 --> 00:21:33.660
And so just knowing that
there are people out there who

00:21:33.660 --> 00:21:35.520
want to see you succeed.

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:39.362
- Can I just say really
quickly on camera--

00:21:39.362 --> 00:21:41.130
I want to jump right back in.

00:21:41.130 --> 00:21:42.133
- Yeah.

00:21:42.133 --> 00:21:49.490
- I think what you're doing,
we need more people such as you

00:21:49.490 --> 00:21:51.766
who just don't let
anything get in their way.

00:21:51.766 --> 00:21:54.480
Because I know I won't let
anything get in my way.

00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:57.940
And I know that
you'll do the same.

00:21:57.940 --> 00:22:00.260
- I appreciate that, Kerry.

00:22:00.260 --> 00:22:03.060
We need more people who are
just possibility thinkers, who

00:22:03.060 --> 00:22:08.180
just do your best when
you feel like at least--

00:22:08.180 --> 00:22:10.440
- Exactly.

00:22:10.440 --> 00:22:11.900
I think we're good.

00:22:11.900 --> 00:22:14.180
[END PLAYBACK]

00:22:14.180 --> 00:22:16.400
KERRY MAGRO: So if I leave
you with anything today,

00:22:16.400 --> 00:22:20.050
I hope it's truly that
you consider yourself,

00:22:20.050 --> 00:22:23.140
what David was saying,
a possibility thinker.

00:22:23.140 --> 00:22:25.660
I think in our community today,
one of the biggest things

00:22:25.660 --> 00:22:28.390
that I see is that
companies look

00:22:28.390 --> 00:22:32.500
at what they can do to help
individuals with disabilities.

00:22:32.500 --> 00:22:35.350
But I think we need to change
that mindset, where we're

00:22:35.350 --> 00:22:39.130
thinking about what
individuals with disabilities

00:22:39.130 --> 00:22:42.370
can do for a company versus
the other side around.

00:22:42.370 --> 00:22:47.410
This, I think, and thinking as a
possibility thinker, like David

00:22:47.410 --> 00:22:51.100
said, can lead to
amazing, amazing change.

00:22:51.100 --> 00:22:53.110
David, now in his
50s, has helped

00:22:53.110 --> 00:22:56.140
employ thousands and
thousands of individuals

00:22:56.140 --> 00:22:59.560
with disabilities simply by
growing up with a disability

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:04.540
and knowing that it is one of
the most untapped markets today

00:23:04.540 --> 00:23:06.040
in the United States.

00:23:06.040 --> 00:23:09.130
So via our Facebook page,
we've had the opportunity

00:23:09.130 --> 00:23:11.380
to interview people with
autism, cerebral palsy,

00:23:11.380 --> 00:23:13.810
down syndrome, ADHD,
but also people

00:23:13.810 --> 00:23:17.307
who have been impacted by
disease, such as David,

00:23:17.307 --> 00:23:18.890
to share their stories
with the world.

00:23:18.890 --> 00:23:22.510
It's given us the opportunity
to have these videos seen

00:23:22.510 --> 00:23:24.740
over 30 million times.

00:23:24.740 --> 00:23:26.470
And we actually
download the videos

00:23:26.470 --> 00:23:31.120
for organizations, both business
organizations and also schools,

00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:34.030
as educational videos
and resources for them,

00:23:34.030 --> 00:23:35.830
for individuals who
simply just want

00:23:35.830 --> 00:23:38.140
to learn from the
perspectives of those

00:23:38.140 --> 00:23:40.870
impacted by a diagnosis.

00:23:40.870 --> 00:23:44.380
So one of the big
initiatives that we do

00:23:44.380 --> 00:23:47.740
is during a month
in October, which

00:23:47.740 --> 00:23:50.680
has been proclaimed from
the Department of Labor

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:53.080
as National Disability
Employment Awareness Month.

00:23:53.080 --> 00:23:56.160
This is also National
Disability Awareness Month,

00:23:56.160 --> 00:23:59.970
where we truly highlight
this untapped potential.

00:23:59.970 --> 00:24:02.350
We highlight stories of
people impacted by diagnosis

00:24:02.350 --> 00:24:04.450
who are succeeding in
the workforce today,

00:24:04.450 --> 00:24:08.440
but then we also highlight the
people who are not necessarily

00:24:08.440 --> 00:24:11.830
having a good time trying to
find employment, like the boy

00:24:11.830 --> 00:24:14.940
I mentioned at the beginning
of my presentation.

00:24:14.940 --> 00:24:16.690
So in addition to the
videos we highlight,

00:24:16.690 --> 00:24:18.970
I also share my own personal
perspective growing up

00:24:18.970 --> 00:24:22.600
with autism in very
quick educational videos,

00:24:22.600 --> 00:24:26.470
which I share with employers
throughout the month of October

00:24:26.470 --> 00:24:29.095
to encourage employment of
those with disabilities.

00:24:29.095 --> 00:24:29.810
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:24:29.810 --> 00:24:32.380
- Every month in October,
the United States Department

00:24:32.380 --> 00:24:35.890
of Labor hosts National
Disability Employment Awareness

00:24:35.890 --> 00:24:37.825
Month, an annual
awareness campaign

00:24:37.825 --> 00:24:40.210
that looks to
celebrate and educate

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:42.100
about disability employment.

00:24:42.100 --> 00:24:45.620
I'm asking you today to
consider supporting the cause,

00:24:45.620 --> 00:24:49.123
hosting events in your
workplace around the month,

00:24:49.123 --> 00:24:51.390
and, if you haven't
already, look

00:24:51.390 --> 00:24:55.050
to employ those with
disabilities in your workplace.

00:24:55.050 --> 00:24:59.490
The idea behind NDEAM,
as they like to call it,

00:24:59.490 --> 00:25:02.920
goes back to 1945 when
Congress passed a law

00:25:02.920 --> 00:25:05.470
saying that the
first week in October

00:25:05.470 --> 00:25:09.190
would be National Employed but
Physically Handicapped Week.

00:25:09.190 --> 00:25:10.930
Today almost one
in five Americans

00:25:10.930 --> 00:25:12.960
has a disability in
the United States,

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:15.990
showing the incredible impact
a month like this can have.

00:25:15.990 --> 00:25:18.695
I have a personal connection
to the disability community

00:25:18.695 --> 00:25:19.730
in autism.

00:25:19.730 --> 00:25:23.620
I was completely non-verbal till
2 and 1/2 years old, diagnosed

00:25:23.620 --> 00:25:25.280
with autism when I was four.

00:25:25.280 --> 00:25:28.350
And today, as an adult, after
years of supports and therapies

00:25:28.350 --> 00:25:30.760
have been able to
hold down five jobs

00:25:30.760 --> 00:25:33.240
as a professional speaker,
bestselling author, film

00:25:33.240 --> 00:25:37.660
consultant, local TV talk show
host, and nonprofit founder

00:25:37.660 --> 00:25:39.790
that mentors and
gives out scholarships

00:25:39.790 --> 00:25:43.060
for students with autism and
disabilities to go to college.

00:25:43.060 --> 00:25:45.820
I now give talks to
companies about disabilities

00:25:45.820 --> 00:25:48.730
in the workforce to educate
about the unique abilities

00:25:48.730 --> 00:25:51.460
individuals with
disabilities can have,

00:25:51.460 --> 00:25:52.945
if given the opportunity.

00:25:52.945 --> 00:25:56.050
I see a future where my
high school mentees, who

00:25:56.050 --> 00:25:59.320
all have autism and are
extremely bright and gifted,

00:25:59.320 --> 00:26:03.100
can transition to adulthood
and succeed in the workforce.

00:26:03.100 --> 00:26:06.940
Some of them may have challenges
at first, but so does everyone.

00:26:06.940 --> 00:26:09.170
With the accommodations
in place,

00:26:09.170 --> 00:26:12.160
you may very well be surprised
by what you see from each

00:26:12.160 --> 00:26:13.780
and every single one of them.

00:26:13.780 --> 00:26:17.970
To conclude, US Secretary
of Labor, Alexander Acosta

00:26:17.970 --> 00:26:20.470
has said Americans
of all abilities

00:26:20.470 --> 00:26:22.810
must have access
to good, safe jobs.

00:26:22.810 --> 00:26:24.390
Smart employers know that.

00:26:24.390 --> 00:26:26.560
Including different
perspectives in problem

00:26:26.560 --> 00:26:29.830
solving situations leads
to better solutions.

00:26:29.830 --> 00:26:32.380
Hiring employees with
diverse abilities

00:26:32.380 --> 00:26:35.260
strengthens their business,
increases competition,

00:26:35.260 --> 00:26:37.410
and drives innovation.

00:26:37.410 --> 00:26:41.860
Dr. Temple Grandin reminds us to
see the person, not the label.

00:26:41.860 --> 00:26:44.160
Together, let's focus
on making inclusion

00:26:44.160 --> 00:26:47.902
celebrated, not only in the
workplace, but in every place

00:26:47.902 --> 00:26:48.610
around the world.

