00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:21.100
Grandin, who is an amazing,
amazing autism advocate.

00:29:21.100 --> 00:29:26.770
One of her biggest quotes is
"see the able, not the label."

00:29:26.770 --> 00:29:29.590
And we truly believe
that disclosure

00:29:29.590 --> 00:29:34.810
is so important for these kids
who are growing and getting

00:29:34.810 --> 00:29:38.590
jobs today to be able
to actually succeed

00:29:38.590 --> 00:29:39.947
in the workforce.

00:29:39.947 --> 00:29:41.530
So it's against the
law to ask someone

00:29:41.530 --> 00:29:43.950
if they have a disability.

00:29:43.950 --> 00:29:46.639
And providing awareness events,
not only during October, which

00:29:46.639 --> 00:29:48.430
is National Disability
Employment Awareness

00:29:48.430 --> 00:29:52.060
Month, but also embracing
diversity all year round

00:29:52.060 --> 00:29:56.500
truly, truly helps connectivity
amongst actual workers

00:29:56.500 --> 00:29:57.370
in the workplace.

00:29:57.370 --> 00:30:00.850
And human resources should
try to be acknowledging

00:30:00.850 --> 00:30:03.670
more and more to not only
individuals with disabilities,

00:30:03.670 --> 00:30:07.120
but non-disabled individuals
who work at companies

00:30:07.120 --> 00:30:10.030
about individuals
with disabilities

00:30:10.030 --> 00:30:13.360
and some of the signs
that they may have.

00:30:13.360 --> 00:30:15.650
Reasonable accommodations
go further,

00:30:15.650 --> 00:30:18.190
taking on a bigger role
with more individuals

00:30:18.190 --> 00:30:21.130
later in life developing
physical disabilities.

00:30:21.130 --> 00:30:23.140
Not only individuals
who are getting

00:30:23.140 --> 00:30:25.480
diagnosed with disabilities
a very early age,

00:30:25.480 --> 00:30:27.670
but as people get
older, developing

00:30:27.670 --> 00:30:31.910
physical disabilities
is very, very common.

00:30:31.910 --> 00:30:33.820
So more awareness
is needed focused

00:30:33.820 --> 00:30:35.680
on the lifespan of
disabilities, not only

00:30:35.680 --> 00:30:39.910
for individuals who are young,
but also individuals as they

00:30:39.910 --> 00:30:42.020
are going into later adulthood.

00:30:42.020 --> 00:30:45.310
So my journey with
autism employment-- now,

00:30:45.310 --> 00:30:47.530
I was told by--

00:30:47.530 --> 00:30:49.480
I was told by
countless people when

00:30:49.480 --> 00:30:53.350
I was in school that it would
be very, very hard for me to get

00:30:53.350 --> 00:30:57.340
a job one day because I would
think very, very literally.

00:30:57.340 --> 00:30:59.230
Sarcasm would go over my head.

00:30:59.230 --> 00:31:02.290
I wouldn't understand
any single joke,

00:31:02.290 --> 00:31:05.550
and I didn't make my first
friend until I was 14.

00:31:05.550 --> 00:31:08.920
So they thought my interpersonal
skills would never give me

00:31:08.920 --> 00:31:11.500
the opportunity to
really become someone who

00:31:11.500 --> 00:31:14.660
could succeed in the workforce.

00:31:14.660 --> 00:31:18.250
And it was a lot
of trial and error.

00:31:18.250 --> 00:31:20.020
My parents became my
greatest advocates

00:31:20.020 --> 00:31:23.740
growing up, truly getting
me through situations where

00:31:23.740 --> 00:31:26.890
we would do mock interviews,
where we would truly

00:31:26.890 --> 00:31:30.790
try to help assess and
transition me to the workforce

00:31:30.790 --> 00:31:34.090
by giving me
schedules and trying

00:31:34.090 --> 00:31:36.520
to help me understand what
the job environment looked

00:31:36.520 --> 00:31:39.670
like before I even went
into that specific job.

00:31:39.670 --> 00:31:42.367
And I think that's something
that could help anyone, truly.

00:31:42.367 --> 00:31:44.200
This gave us the
opportunity to give two TED

00:31:44.200 --> 00:31:46.600
Talks in the past five years.

00:31:46.600 --> 00:31:50.710
The first talk in my local
community in New Jersey,

00:31:50.710 --> 00:31:52.720
The Will of Opportunity--
the Path of Autism

00:31:52.720 --> 00:31:57.400
to College, which focuses
on those individuals who

00:31:57.400 --> 00:32:00.220
have autism pursuing a
post-secondary education,

00:32:00.220 --> 00:32:06.040
but then also finding internship
opportunities in the workforce.

00:32:06.040 --> 00:32:08.930
And then the second one, What
Happens to Children with Autism

00:32:08.930 --> 00:32:12.400
When They Become Adults,
focuses on a question

00:32:12.400 --> 00:32:15.940
that hits a lot of families,
especially parents.

00:32:15.940 --> 00:32:19.030
And that is, what will happen
to my child when I'm gone?

00:32:19.030 --> 00:32:22.210
In our community today,
especially in the autism

00:32:22.210 --> 00:32:26.920
community, over 500,000
individuals with autism

00:32:26.920 --> 00:32:32.080
will be reaching adulthood
within the next decade.

00:32:32.080 --> 00:32:34.540
Untapped potential,
untapped market

00:32:34.540 --> 00:32:36.250
of individuals who
will be reaching

00:32:36.250 --> 00:32:38.320
adulthood, and many
of these individuals

00:32:38.320 --> 00:32:40.852
will be highly skilled.

00:32:40.852 --> 00:32:42.310
Some of the kids
I know with autism

00:32:42.310 --> 00:32:45.530
are the brightest
kids in the world.

00:32:45.530 --> 00:32:48.880
And my friend
Temple Grandin once

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:51.910
said that she believes
that half of Silicon Valley

00:32:51.910 --> 00:32:54.220
is actually on the
autism spectrum

00:32:54.220 --> 00:32:56.140
because they think
literally, they're

00:32:56.140 --> 00:32:58.910
able to do one-on-one
projects so simply,

00:32:58.910 --> 00:33:02.000
and they're some of the most
brightest people you would ever

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:02.500
meet.

00:33:02.500 --> 00:33:06.020
So that just goes
into another quote,

00:33:06.020 --> 00:33:07.750
which I share a lot of time.

00:33:07.750 --> 00:33:11.110
It's that when we're
thinking about the how

00:33:11.110 --> 00:33:15.820
to get these individuals
hired, it's best to think of it

00:33:15.820 --> 00:33:18.040
as this quote right
here, which says,

00:33:18.040 --> 00:33:20.470
"If you've met one
individual with a disability,

00:33:20.470 --> 00:33:23.500
you've truly met one
individual with a disability,"

00:33:23.500 --> 00:33:26.410
regardless of its autism or not.

00:33:26.410 --> 00:33:31.060
There's no one size fits all
for a proper way of hiring

00:33:31.060 --> 00:33:32.300
someone with a disability.

00:33:32.300 --> 00:33:35.740
So it's truly important to
create your own blueprint

00:33:35.740 --> 00:33:38.200
of what that looks like
by simply getting to know

00:33:38.200 --> 00:33:42.430
and establishing a rapport with
the individuals you work with.

00:33:42.430 --> 00:33:44.770
That can mean
anything from having

00:33:44.770 --> 00:33:47.205
more social outings
after work for people

00:33:47.205 --> 00:33:48.580
to get to know
each other better,

00:33:48.580 --> 00:33:53.500
from peer mentoring programs,
for actual summits where

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:56.860
individuals can have more
opportunities to network

00:33:56.860 --> 00:33:58.300
with each other.

00:33:58.300 --> 00:34:00.760
But also at the same time,
one of the biggest things

00:34:00.760 --> 00:34:03.880
we talk about in a [INAUDIBLE]
basis, the importance

00:34:03.880 --> 00:34:05.080
of self-reflection.

00:34:05.080 --> 00:34:08.230
And actually, we
encourage many employees,

00:34:08.230 --> 00:34:11.380
both with disabilities and
not, to have journal entries,

00:34:11.380 --> 00:34:15.460
to continue to self reflect on
their strengths and weaknesses.

00:34:15.460 --> 00:34:18.025
Because, especially in
our disability community,

00:34:18.025 --> 00:34:19.900
one of my favorite quotes
from Temple Grandin

00:34:19.900 --> 00:34:22.989
is "interests and talents
can truly turn into careers."

00:34:22.989 --> 00:34:26.090
But for many individuals
with disabilities,

00:34:26.090 --> 00:34:28.480
they may not necessarily
think about their strengths

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:30.340
a lot of times
because they're so

00:34:30.340 --> 00:34:33.460
focused on trying to overcome
some of the weaknesses

00:34:33.460 --> 00:34:36.130
to find a job.

00:34:36.130 --> 00:34:40.159
So seven ways I truly
found employment today,

00:34:40.159 --> 00:34:42.670
the number one was honing
in on my key interests,

00:34:42.670 --> 00:34:46.150
which I'll talk a little bit
later in this presentation.

00:34:46.150 --> 00:34:48.159
Becoming a
self-advocate-- when I

00:34:48.159 --> 00:34:50.980
was going to college
for the first time,

00:34:50.980 --> 00:34:53.199
so in school, individuals
with disabilities

00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:56.780
can get an IEP, which is the
Individual Education Plan.

00:34:56.780 --> 00:34:59.140
And when I was
going to college, I

00:34:59.140 --> 00:35:01.370
received no transitional
services in high school,

00:35:01.370 --> 00:35:04.840
so I actually went up to my
post-secondary disability

00:35:04.840 --> 00:35:07.850
support specialist
and I told her,

00:35:07.850 --> 00:35:09.700
if you could just hook
me up with my IEP,

00:35:09.700 --> 00:35:11.750
I'll be out of here and
I'll be ready to go.

00:35:11.750 --> 00:35:15.490
And she said, child,
sit down, and told me

00:35:15.490 --> 00:35:19.240
for the first time about
reasonable accommodations.

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:21.370
And I never, never
knew about it.

00:35:21.370 --> 00:35:24.010
So I had to become
a self advocate.

00:35:24.010 --> 00:35:26.610
And I was very
deer-in-headlights at the time.

00:35:26.610 --> 00:35:30.130
However, I took it in stride.

00:35:30.130 --> 00:35:33.220
I took less credits to
really understand the need

00:35:33.220 --> 00:35:34.600
to become a self advocate.

00:35:34.600 --> 00:35:38.560
And having that impact at a very
early age in college actually

00:35:38.560 --> 00:35:43.810
helped propel me to finding jobs
once I graduated from college.

00:35:43.810 --> 00:35:48.360
Asking questions is
another big thing, I think.

00:35:48.360 --> 00:35:52.300
And it may seem cliche, but
we still, as a community,

00:35:52.300 --> 00:35:54.700
sometimes don't
ask some questions

00:35:54.700 --> 00:35:56.920
because we think they're
going to be dumb questions.

00:35:56.920 --> 00:35:59.530
And there is no such
thing as a dumb question.

00:35:59.530 --> 00:36:02.500
Really make sure that
you're focused on that.

00:36:02.500 --> 00:36:07.300
So doing research on job careers
is also very, very important.

00:36:07.300 --> 00:36:10.980
Realizing I couldn't
live by a label,

00:36:10.980 --> 00:36:13.910
self-reflection
exercises were critical.

00:36:13.910 --> 00:36:15.790
I've been writing
in a journal since I

00:36:15.790 --> 00:36:18.940
was 12 years old about my
strengths and weaknesses.

00:36:18.940 --> 00:36:22.090
When I found out I had
autism at 11 and 1/2,

00:36:22.090 --> 00:36:25.940
we were playing celebrity
disability bingo

00:36:25.940 --> 00:36:27.710
in one of my social
skills classes,

00:36:27.710 --> 00:36:30.550
and I was learning that people
like Michael Jordan had ADD.

00:36:30.550 --> 00:36:32.270
Magic Johnson had ADHD.

00:36:32.270 --> 00:36:35.560
And I asked, why am I special,
to my social skills teacher.

00:36:35.560 --> 00:36:37.900
And she's like, oh, you
have to talk to your parents

00:36:37.900 --> 00:36:38.650
about that.

00:36:38.650 --> 00:36:41.590
And after school, that was
the first time they told me

00:36:41.590 --> 00:36:42.790
I had autism.

00:36:42.790 --> 00:36:46.600
But after that, I started
writing journal entries

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:48.760
based on just going
into IEP meetings

00:36:48.760 --> 00:36:50.890
to learn about my
strengths and weaknesses.

00:36:50.890 --> 00:36:54.010
And then, finally, role
playing different situations,

00:36:54.010 --> 00:36:57.430
such as mock interview
processes, truly helped me.

00:36:57.430 --> 00:37:01.060
So the two interests that
helped me growing up--

00:37:01.060 --> 00:37:01.960
first was theater.

00:37:01.960 --> 00:37:04.210
I wanted to be the sixth
member of the Backstreet Boys

00:37:04.210 --> 00:37:04.870
growing up.

00:37:04.870 --> 00:37:07.750
For my 11th birthday I
wanted the white suit

00:37:07.750 --> 00:37:10.500
from the "I Want
It That Way" video.

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:13.480
So I was clearly a dork.

00:37:13.480 --> 00:37:16.080
I still am a dork a little bit.

00:37:16.080 --> 00:37:19.080
But I fell in love
with music therapy.

00:37:19.080 --> 00:37:20.790
At a time when I was
having difficulties

00:37:20.790 --> 00:37:23.490
with loud noises,
bright lights, there

00:37:23.490 --> 00:37:26.289
was always something
soothing about being onstage,

00:37:26.289 --> 00:37:28.080
even though the lights
were there, but also

00:37:28.080 --> 00:37:30.480
something soothing about music.

00:37:30.480 --> 00:37:33.960
So I stuck to theater
for about 15 years,

00:37:33.960 --> 00:37:36.690
and once I graduated
from high school

00:37:36.690 --> 00:37:38.550
I became an autism
advocate and found

00:37:38.550 --> 00:37:41.280
one of my first jobs,
which was to be an autism

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:43.380
consultant on major
motion pictures

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:46.490
based on my focus on the
entertainment industry,

00:37:46.490 --> 00:37:49.320
getting to work on films
such as "Joyful Noise," which

00:37:49.320 --> 00:37:52.200
stars a teenager with
autism in the film.

00:37:52.200 --> 00:37:54.540
Other films such as
"Jane Wants a Boyfriend,"

00:37:54.540 --> 00:37:56.430
which focuses on
a girl with autism

00:37:56.430 --> 00:37:58.680
trying to find love
in New York City,

00:37:58.680 --> 00:38:02.070
and then also consulting on
documentaries such as "Big

00:38:02.070 --> 00:38:04.320
Daddy Autism," which
looks at a single dad

00:38:04.320 --> 00:38:06.470
with a nonverbal
child on the spectrum.

00:38:06.470 --> 00:38:09.510
And "Don't Foil My Plans,"
which goes into the employment

00:38:09.510 --> 00:38:11.940
background, actually
focuses on employment

00:38:11.940 --> 00:38:15.100
for those with disabilities.

00:38:15.100 --> 00:38:18.570
And then basketball-- I want
to be the next Larry Bird.

00:38:18.570 --> 00:38:22.080
So I integrated basketball
into my physical therapy.

00:38:22.080 --> 00:38:24.000
Growing up I could
tell you all 30 NBA

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.130
teams and every single
player on those teams,

00:38:26.130 --> 00:38:28.780
simply because it was
one of my key interests.

00:38:28.780 --> 00:38:30.700
And once I graduated
from high school,

00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:33.870
I didn't get any Division
I offers-- womp, womp.

00:38:33.870 --> 00:38:37.770
But I got involved
with NBA Cares, which

00:38:37.770 --> 00:38:39.750
is a nonprofit
organization, getting

00:38:39.750 --> 00:38:42.180
to interview countless
NBA celebrities

00:38:42.180 --> 00:38:47.340
to share the impact sports
can have on individuals

00:38:47.340 --> 00:38:48.990
with disabilities,
and asking them

00:38:48.990 --> 00:38:52.350
to consider getting involved
with philanthropic causes

00:38:52.350 --> 00:38:55.110
towards our special
need community.

00:38:55.110 --> 00:38:59.130
So hiring people with autism
and other disabilities

00:38:59.130 --> 00:39:01.860
truly just makes
good business sense.

00:39:01.860 --> 00:39:04.140
Customers with disabilities
and their families,

00:39:04.140 --> 00:39:06.600
for those in this
room who don't know,

00:39:06.600 --> 00:39:09.420
represent a trillion
dollar market today

00:39:09.420 --> 00:39:10.490
in the United States.

00:39:10.490 --> 00:39:12.370
They, like other
market segments,

00:39:12.370 --> 00:39:14.940
purchase products and
services from companies

00:39:14.940 --> 00:39:16.950
that best meet their needs.

00:39:16.950 --> 00:39:19.500
And a large number
of Americans today

00:39:19.500 --> 00:39:22.170
say that they would prefer
to patronize businesses that

00:39:22.170 --> 00:39:24.040
hire people with disabilities.

00:39:24.040 --> 00:39:26.820
And then, finally, businesses
across the United States

00:39:26.820 --> 00:39:29.550
have begun to realize that
hiring talented candidates

00:39:29.550 --> 00:39:32.940
with disabilities is not
only the right thing to do,

00:39:32.940 --> 00:39:35.310
it makes good business
sense while demonstrating

00:39:35.310 --> 00:39:39.690
high return on investment
and aids in 503 compliance,

00:39:39.690 --> 00:39:42.720
which every
organization has to do.

00:39:42.720 --> 00:39:44.677
So how to manage employees
with disabilities?

00:39:44.677 --> 00:39:47.010
This is actually one of the
biggest questions we usually

00:39:47.010 --> 00:39:48.420
get during a Q&amp;A period.

00:39:48.420 --> 00:39:50.430
And one of the biggest
things, don't come in

00:39:50.430 --> 00:39:53.490
with any unperceived notions.

00:39:53.490 --> 00:39:57.390
We say that sometimes
we think in a box,

00:39:57.390 --> 00:40:02.100
and you have to think
outside the box as well.

00:40:02.100 --> 00:40:04.830
Document challenges and
strengths in the workplace.

00:40:04.830 --> 00:40:09.690
Please use concrete language
as much as you possibly can.

00:40:09.690 --> 00:40:14.760
And take your time when you're
talking to these individuals

00:40:14.760 --> 00:40:17.040
and make sure that they
know what you said.

00:40:17.040 --> 00:40:18.930
And if they ask
you to repeat it,

00:40:18.930 --> 00:40:21.090
sometimes that's going to
be what you have to do.

00:40:21.090 --> 00:40:23.730
Make sure all team building
events are accessible.

00:40:23.730 --> 00:40:25.230
This is huge.

00:40:25.230 --> 00:40:28.710
I've seen so many convocations
where events have happened

00:40:28.710 --> 00:40:31.650
with things such as no
wheelchair accessibility,

00:40:31.650 --> 00:40:35.620
and it literally blows
my mind to this day.

00:40:35.620 --> 00:40:39.990
I would also definitely look
at a leadership book called

00:40:39.990 --> 00:40:41.580
"The New One Minute Manager."

00:40:41.580 --> 00:40:43.950
it's a fantastic,
fantastic book that

00:40:43.950 --> 00:40:46.515
really looks at how you
can go about establishing

00:40:46.515 --> 00:40:50.040
a rapport with your employees.

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:51.900
And offer professional
development training

00:40:51.900 --> 00:40:54.090
by bringing in experts
and individuals

00:40:54.090 --> 00:40:56.130
with disabilities
who have successfully

00:40:56.130 --> 00:40:58.090
navigated the workplace.

00:40:58.090 --> 00:41:01.320
These are some examples of
success stories of corporations

00:41:01.320 --> 00:41:05.097
today who are currently hiring
individuals with disabilities.

00:41:05.097 --> 00:41:07.680
One of the common themes you'll
see in many of these companies

00:41:07.680 --> 00:41:10.800
is that they have a high
focus on technology,

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:14.260
the SAPs of the world, the
Freddie Macs of the world.

00:41:14.260 --> 00:41:16.740
So there is a focus
on those STEM jobs

00:41:16.740 --> 00:41:18.960
that are really helping
these individuals.

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:23.280
So finally, I just want to share
with you some quotes from some

00:41:23.280 --> 00:41:27.750
of my mentees on what
disabilities and trying to find

00:41:27.750 --> 00:41:29.170
employment means to them.

00:41:29.170 --> 00:41:32.250
So one individual,
Ron Sandinson,

00:41:32.250 --> 00:41:36.630
he's one of the first
pastors to ever have autism.

00:41:36.630 --> 00:41:40.620
And he want people to know,
"Employers, we with autism

00:41:40.620 --> 00:41:43.980
would love for you to understand
that not all disabilities are

00:41:43.980 --> 00:41:45.000
visible.

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:46.890
When we don't look
you in the eye,

00:41:46.890 --> 00:41:50.502
it does not mean
we aren't there.

00:41:50.502 --> 00:41:51.960
If we fail to shake
your hand or we

00:41:51.960 --> 00:41:53.820
say something not
appropriate, it does not

00:41:53.820 --> 00:41:55.530
mean we're trying to be rude.

00:41:55.530 --> 00:41:57.920
When we need extra
clarification to do the job,

00:41:57.920 --> 00:42:00.450
it does not mean we
are slow or stupid.

00:42:00.450 --> 00:42:03.210
Due to autism, we process
information differently,

00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:06.480
but we also have amazing gifts
like attention to details

00:42:06.480 --> 00:42:09.680
and faithful to attended work."

00:42:09.680 --> 00:42:11.970
And then I love this guy.

00:42:11.970 --> 00:42:14.160
Matthew, who's aspiring
accountant, he says,

00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:16.050
"When working with
people with autism,

00:42:16.050 --> 00:42:18.480
it's best not to focus
on how they appear.

00:42:18.480 --> 00:42:20.040
I feel it is more
important to focus

00:42:20.040 --> 00:42:23.980
on their work and the
outcomes of that work.

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:26.910
Even if they look
uninterested and unfocused,

00:42:26.910 --> 00:42:29.040
they probably are
interested and focused.

00:42:29.040 --> 00:42:31.345
They likely care more
than they let on.

00:42:31.345 --> 00:42:33.720
And to quote the 'Transformer'
movie, which he absolutely

00:42:33.720 --> 00:42:36.480
loves, there is 'more
than meets the eye'

00:42:36.480 --> 00:42:39.390
for individuals with autism."

00:42:39.390 --> 00:42:42.720
So finally, what employers
need to focus on today

00:42:42.720 --> 00:42:47.320
is clear job responsibilities
more than anything else.

00:42:47.320 --> 00:42:49.650
If you go to the Department
of Labor's website,

00:42:49.650 --> 00:42:52.140
they have an amazing,
amazing booklet

00:42:52.140 --> 00:42:54.210
called "The Business
Strategies that

00:42:54.210 --> 00:42:56.852
Work-- a Framework for
Disability Inclusion."

00:42:56.852 --> 00:42:57.810
The link is right here.

00:42:57.810 --> 00:42:59.490
I'd highly recommend
for anyone who's

00:42:59.490 --> 00:43:02.160
looking to hire more
individuals with disabilities

00:43:02.160 --> 00:43:05.940
in their workplace to give
it a very thorough look.

00:43:05.940 --> 00:43:07.800
It has some guidelines
on everything

00:43:07.800 --> 00:43:09.870
we're talking today
about job descriptions,

00:43:09.870 --> 00:43:12.690
to how you can host
diversity events

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:16.230
in your workplace towards
individuals with disabilities.

00:43:16.230 --> 00:43:20.040
And I've seen it help countless,
countless companies today.

00:43:20.040 --> 00:43:27.120
So just as a final thought, I
never thought that any of this

00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:28.560
was going to be possible.

00:43:28.560 --> 00:43:31.050
When I was growing
up, people told me

00:43:31.050 --> 00:43:35.340
that it would be very, very
unlikely that I would even

00:43:35.340 --> 00:43:36.510
get to college.

00:43:36.510 --> 00:43:38.910
And now the thing I can say
is that even though it's

00:43:38.910 --> 00:43:41.760
a spectrum, disability
is a spectrum,

00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:44.730
and some kids are going to be on
the severe end, who might need

00:43:44.730 --> 00:43:47.670
lifetime care, I
can truly say today

00:43:47.670 --> 00:43:51.240
that we as a community
in the United States

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:55.140
are the most diverse in
our history right now.

00:43:55.140 --> 00:44:00.030
And we need to think about ways
we can think outside of the box

00:44:00.030 --> 00:44:04.620
towards maximizing the potential
of all of our companies.

00:44:04.620 --> 00:44:08.490
And with that, I couldn't
think of a better way

00:44:08.490 --> 00:44:12.600
than trying to maximize and
utilize the potential of some

00:44:12.600 --> 00:44:15.480
of these amazing,
amazing individuals

00:44:15.480 --> 00:44:19.320
with disabilities, as long as
we just give them the chance

00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:22.320
to show what they're made of.

00:44:22.320 --> 00:44:24.331
Thank you all so much
for having me today.

00:44:24.331 --> 00:44:27.097
