Thank you all so
much for coming out.

00:44:38.630 --> 00:44:40.331
Yes?

00:44:40.331 --> 00:44:43.280
AUDIENCE: So I'm curious,
what specific reasonable

00:44:43.280 --> 00:44:48.140
accommodations tend to be
most useful for employees

00:44:48.140 --> 00:44:48.660
with autism?

00:44:48.660 --> 00:44:52.552
And to what extent do they
have success in getting them?

00:44:52.552 --> 00:44:54.260
KERRY MAGRO: So most
of the time they do.

00:44:54.260 --> 00:44:59.390
Again, most individuals who file
for reasonable accommodations,

00:44:59.390 --> 00:45:03.740
accommodations can be anything
from written explanations

00:45:03.740 --> 00:45:07.370
to specific tasks
for specific projects

00:45:07.370 --> 00:45:08.720
that they're supposed to do.

00:45:08.720 --> 00:45:11.850
Lots of people with autism
think in many different ways.

00:45:11.850 --> 00:45:13.320
Some people think in pictures.

00:45:13.320 --> 00:45:15.260
Some people think visually.

00:45:15.260 --> 00:45:17.350
Some people think in auditory.

00:45:17.350 --> 00:45:19.490
So sometimes they
will give things

00:45:19.490 --> 00:45:22.340
such as written explanations
on all of their projects.

00:45:22.340 --> 00:45:24.200
Sometimes they could
ask for accommodation

00:45:24.200 --> 00:45:26.930
where they could get e-mails
versus actually having

00:45:26.930 --> 00:45:30.530
to hear a verbal
project, and kind of just

00:45:30.530 --> 00:45:35.210
have a breakdown with either
their current boss or someone

00:45:35.210 --> 00:45:37.070
who was part of a human
resource department.

00:45:37.070 --> 00:45:40.070
That's usually what
we see the most.

00:45:40.070 --> 00:45:43.940
But then we also
see accommodations

00:45:43.940 --> 00:45:49.490
such as being able to bring a
recorder for some team meetings

00:45:49.490 --> 00:45:51.350
to actually be able to--

00:45:51.350 --> 00:45:55.100
a confidential
recorder-- to actually

00:45:55.100 --> 00:45:59.090
be able to listen to the actual
assignments that they're given,

00:45:59.090 --> 00:46:02.640
and also to provide it for
feedback for them as well.

00:46:02.640 --> 00:46:04.679
So those are the
two biggest ones

00:46:04.679 --> 00:46:06.970
that are currently helping
individuals in the workplace

00:46:06.970 --> 00:46:08.610
today that we recommend.

00:46:08.610 --> 00:46:09.440
Hope that helped.

00:46:09.440 --> 00:46:11.690
Yes?

00:46:11.690 --> 00:46:15.150
AUDIENCE: The notion of
clear job responsibilities

00:46:15.150 --> 00:46:16.070
is very interesting.

00:46:16.070 --> 00:46:20.030
We've-- well, thinking about
performance evaluation for some

00:46:20.030 --> 00:46:25.250
reason, as well as hiring,
I found that it's difficult

00:46:25.250 --> 00:46:28.400
for companies to phrase their
job requirements in that

00:46:28.400 --> 00:46:29.780
concrete terms.

00:46:29.780 --> 00:46:33.150
So any hints on how
we can do that better?

00:46:33.150 --> 00:46:35.330
KERRY MAGRO: So one
of the biggest things

00:46:35.330 --> 00:46:40.870
is when someone actually
does apply for a job,

00:46:40.870 --> 00:46:42.900
it is a process.

00:46:42.900 --> 00:46:45.740
And one of the biggest things
I say, it's not a sprint.

00:46:45.740 --> 00:46:48.710
Most of the time it is
very much a marathon

00:46:48.710 --> 00:46:51.590
when it comes to each
unique individual who

00:46:51.590 --> 00:46:52.820
may be applying for this job.

00:46:52.820 --> 00:46:55.280
One of the biggest
things I would truly say

00:46:55.280 --> 00:46:58.250
is to really think about--

00:46:58.250 --> 00:47:00.870
we try to think of this
as an annual perspective.

00:47:00.870 --> 00:47:03.680
So we think about
the job projects

00:47:03.680 --> 00:47:07.250
that an individual might
have for out the year,

00:47:07.250 --> 00:47:11.660
and we try to talk to companies
about how we can kind of just

00:47:11.660 --> 00:47:13.770
pinpoint some specific areas.

00:47:13.770 --> 00:47:16.340
So for example, one of
the things that we'll do

00:47:16.340 --> 00:47:19.310
is we'll talk to
a human resource

00:47:19.310 --> 00:47:22.740
department about
if, for example,

00:47:22.740 --> 00:47:24.890
they're in the technology
field and they have

00:47:24.890 --> 00:47:26.840
to do a certain amount
of code or they have

00:47:26.840 --> 00:47:29.660
to do JavaScript and
focus on a website,

00:47:29.660 --> 00:47:32.552
we kind of say, we need
to have HTML in here.

00:47:32.552 --> 00:47:34.010
We need to have
JavaScript in here.

00:47:34.010 --> 00:47:36.470
So we kind of try
to make it not only

00:47:36.470 --> 00:47:39.650
concrete, but as descriptive
as humanly possible.

00:47:39.650 --> 00:47:44.790
Many job applications
today are only one page,

00:47:44.790 --> 00:47:47.960
which we see on a lot of sites
like monster.com and LinkedIn.

00:47:47.960 --> 00:47:51.500
So we try to make sure that
it's not only concrete,

00:47:51.500 --> 00:47:54.320
but its also as descriptive
as humanly possible

00:47:54.320 --> 00:47:56.900
because those are two
different channels completely.

00:47:56.900 --> 00:47:58.590
So it's not only
about being concrete,

00:47:58.590 --> 00:48:00.830
but it's also making
sure that you list out

00:48:00.830 --> 00:48:03.010
every single
requirement that you're

00:48:03.010 --> 00:48:05.510
going to need for that person
as well, especially if they're

00:48:05.510 --> 00:48:07.940
doing a very specific
job that is already

00:48:07.940 --> 00:48:10.950
going to need proper training
before they go into the job.

00:48:10.950 --> 00:48:11.770
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:11.770 --> 00:48:12.020
KERRY MAGRO: Hi.

00:48:12.020 --> 00:48:13.065
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:48:13.065 --> 00:48:13.730
KERRY MAGRO: Glad to be here.

00:48:13.730 --> 00:48:15.920
AUDIENCE: I am an
intern recruiter here.

00:48:15.920 --> 00:48:18.890
And I've worked with several
candidates who have autism.

00:48:18.890 --> 00:48:21.470
Happy to say that many of them
will be joining us this summer

00:48:21.470 --> 00:48:23.370
as engineers, which is awesome.

00:48:23.370 --> 00:48:23.740
KERRY MAGRO: That's amazing.

00:48:23.740 --> 00:48:24.240
Congrats.

00:48:24.240 --> 00:48:25.130
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:48:25.130 --> 00:48:26.360
So I have a question.

00:48:26.360 --> 00:48:28.100
I'm just curious if you--

00:48:28.100 --> 00:48:31.130
I know you mentioned companies
obviously can't ask people

00:48:31.130 --> 00:48:33.350
if they have a disability.

00:48:33.350 --> 00:48:37.430
And I think you said that you
advise students, candidates

00:48:37.430 --> 00:48:39.260
to self-disclose.

00:48:39.260 --> 00:48:42.470
I'm curious what your advice
is like when you tell them

00:48:42.470 --> 00:48:44.566
that they should
be self-disclosing,

00:48:44.566 --> 00:48:46.190
if it's at the
beginning of the process

00:48:46.190 --> 00:48:47.944
or what the timing
of that is like.

00:48:47.944 --> 00:48:50.360
KERRY MAGRO: So one of the
biggest things with individuals

00:48:50.360 --> 00:48:54.230
with disabilities we see is
that, if you don't disclose

00:48:54.230 --> 00:48:56.870
right away, it becomes very,
very difficult once they

00:48:56.870 --> 00:48:59.000
actually get into
the workforce to get

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:02.687
those reasonable accommodations
versus actually disclosing

00:49:02.687 --> 00:49:04.520
right ahead of time,
because usually there's

00:49:04.520 --> 00:49:06.500
a few weeks before an
employer will actually

00:49:06.500 --> 00:49:10.280
start the actual
internship or position.

00:49:10.280 --> 00:49:12.110
So that gives the human
resource department

00:49:12.110 --> 00:49:16.070
a possibility to talk to the
specific boss of that employee

00:49:16.070 --> 00:49:18.500
about what some of the
accommodations are going to be.

00:49:18.500 --> 00:49:23.070
So if someone, for example, goes
in two, three weeks and says,

00:49:23.070 --> 00:49:23.730
you know what?

00:49:23.730 --> 00:49:25.146
I need a reasonable
accommodation,

00:49:25.146 --> 00:49:28.130
and doesn't, it kind of
brings in a very tough

00:49:28.130 --> 00:49:29.249
transitional phase.

00:49:29.249 --> 00:49:31.040
And for many individuals
with disabilities,

00:49:31.040 --> 00:49:34.580
along with autism, that I
know have very difficult times

00:49:34.580 --> 00:49:36.440
at times with
transitions and being

00:49:36.440 --> 00:49:38.570
able to go through
that, especially

00:49:38.570 --> 00:49:41.690
when you think of many
individuals to this day--

00:49:41.690 --> 00:49:45.050
I know adults love things
like visual schedules

00:49:45.050 --> 00:49:48.290
and will have these
schedules in either a book

00:49:48.290 --> 00:49:50.450
that they bring
around with them where

00:49:50.450 --> 00:49:52.970
they have everything set up.

00:49:52.970 --> 00:49:57.410
They need to do it right away
to avoid misunderstandings,

00:49:57.410 --> 00:49:59.160
miscommunication
at a later time,

00:49:59.160 --> 00:50:02.900
especially with transitions,
but also with the communication

00:50:02.900 --> 00:50:05.060
with their boss and their team.

00:50:05.060 --> 00:50:08.371
So that's the number one reason
why we encourage disclosure

00:50:08.371 --> 00:50:08.870
right away.

00:50:08.870 --> 00:50:09.280
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

