00:50:30.310 --> 00:50:31.979
KERRY MAGRO: Absolutely.

00:50:31.979 --> 00:50:33.520
AUDIENCE: So in your
experience, what

00:50:33.520 --> 00:50:37.750
have you seen has worked for
people on the autism spectrum

00:50:37.750 --> 00:50:43.610
in terms of specifically
sensory accommodations?

00:50:43.610 --> 00:50:46.570
KERRY MAGRO: Well,
I know sensory-wise,

00:50:46.570 --> 00:50:51.670
so actually in companies
I would always--

00:50:51.670 --> 00:50:53.781
and this has
gradually slowed down

00:50:53.781 --> 00:50:55.030
as I've gotten a little older.

00:50:55.030 --> 00:50:58.250
But I've always used
a sensory brush,

00:50:58.250 --> 00:51:00.850
which is like the size
of my palm for whenever

00:51:00.850 --> 00:51:02.050
I would have a situation.

00:51:02.050 --> 00:51:04.404
Now, I know, obviously, many
reasonable accommodation

00:51:04.404 --> 00:51:06.070
in the workplace,
they don't necessarily

00:51:06.070 --> 00:51:07.900
provide a sensory brush.

00:51:07.900 --> 00:51:11.890
But things-- for example,
I've seen a lot of individuals

00:51:11.890 --> 00:51:15.610
with sensory issues
prefer to use

00:51:15.610 --> 00:51:17.410
laptops for all
their assignments

00:51:17.410 --> 00:51:20.330
versus any written projects,
which is very accessible now

00:51:20.330 --> 00:51:23.770
because we're trying to go green
in many companies today anyway.

00:51:23.770 --> 00:51:28.450
So utilizing assistive
technology, laptops,

00:51:28.450 --> 00:51:31.870
especially for
more sensory issues

00:51:31.870 --> 00:51:36.250
that are focused on
just holding things

00:51:36.250 --> 00:51:37.630
such as pencils and pens.

00:51:37.630 --> 00:51:40.630
There might be textural
issues that individuals

00:51:40.630 --> 00:51:43.870
might deal with,
especially if they're

00:51:43.870 --> 00:51:46.900
provided in certain ways,
like having to write on paper,

00:51:46.900 --> 00:51:50.360
having to write even on a
white board or a smart board

00:51:50.360 --> 00:51:52.070
it might be difficult for them.

00:51:52.070 --> 00:51:55.450
So being able to utilize
their assistive technology,

00:51:55.450 --> 00:51:59.960
whether it be an iPad or being
able to use a computer as well.

00:51:59.960 --> 00:52:02.230
So that's one of the bigger
reasonable accommodations

00:52:02.230 --> 00:52:04.330
we see, especially
on the sensory realm.

00:52:04.330 --> 00:52:09.972
And it's going to vary for
person to person as well.

00:52:09.972 --> 00:52:10.840
Hope that helps.

00:52:10.840 --> 00:52:11.800
Yes?

00:52:11.800 --> 00:52:14.200
AUDIENCE: I'm just
wondering if individual

00:52:14.200 --> 00:52:16.920
doesn't self-disclose,
is it polite

00:52:16.920 --> 00:52:22.570
and advised to ask if you
think, OK, maybe if I knew that.

00:52:22.570 --> 00:52:25.690
What are the better ways to
communicate, for example?

00:52:25.690 --> 00:52:29.050
Like whether verbal
communication or written

00:52:29.050 --> 00:52:31.860
communication should be used.

00:52:31.860 --> 00:52:34.690
What's the best
way to approach it?

00:52:34.690 --> 00:52:36.370
KERRY MAGRO: Well
the thing we see

00:52:36.370 --> 00:52:41.020
the most is that when companies
do decide to get involved

00:52:41.020 --> 00:52:43.930
with professional
training and then decide

00:52:43.930 --> 00:52:49.060
to get involved with really
trying to show diversity

00:52:49.060 --> 00:52:54.520
in their workplace, it becomes
a more enlightening organization

00:52:54.520 --> 00:52:57.430
to have that aha moment where
they're like, you know what?

00:52:57.430 --> 00:53:01.060
Maybe we can disclose a
disability, versus a company

00:53:01.060 --> 00:53:05.710
where they don't necessarily see
those specific accommodations.

00:53:05.710 --> 00:53:09.490
I've gone into many
companies where even

00:53:09.490 --> 00:53:12.460
being able to be
wheelchair accessible

00:53:12.460 --> 00:53:16.240
and being able to have very
visual signs of that has even

00:53:16.240 --> 00:53:18.790
actually come off
to a domino effect

00:53:18.790 --> 00:53:20.660
for individuals with
learning disabilities,

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:22.034
saying that they're
doing so much

00:53:22.034 --> 00:53:24.940
for physical disabilities that
could trickle down for those

00:53:24.940 --> 00:53:26.710
with learning
disabilities and are more

00:53:26.710 --> 00:53:28.690
likely to want to disclose.

00:53:28.690 --> 00:53:31.180
So it's not only
the visuals that

00:53:31.180 --> 00:53:33.760
are around each and
every specific company,

00:53:33.760 --> 00:53:35.710
but it's also hosting
special events

00:53:35.710 --> 00:53:38.470
and professional training
to focus on diversity

00:53:38.470 --> 00:53:40.670
inclusion in the workplace.

00:53:40.670 --> 00:53:43.630
AUDIENCE: So my example
is, for example, I

00:53:43.630 --> 00:53:46.190
was working an
individual, which appear

00:53:46.190 --> 00:53:50.630
to like not paying attention
to what we were doing.

00:53:50.630 --> 00:53:54.250
And later I learned
that the individual

00:53:54.250 --> 00:53:55.900
was on autism spectrum.

00:53:55.900 --> 00:53:59.360
And had I known that,
maybe I tried harder

00:53:59.360 --> 00:54:02.510
or tried different
ways of communicating.

00:54:02.510 --> 00:54:06.880
So is it something
that's reasonable to ask

00:54:06.880 --> 00:54:08.740
directly or not?

00:54:08.740 --> 00:54:09.940
KERRY MAGRO: No.

00:54:09.940 --> 00:54:11.000
Unfortunately, not.

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:14.065
It's because you have to
think about the individual

00:54:14.065 --> 00:54:17.800
in that case and
what their reaction

00:54:17.800 --> 00:54:20.020
might be if that is brought up.

00:54:20.020 --> 00:54:22.390
And that could lead to
problems down the line

00:54:22.390 --> 00:54:25.270
with work effectiveness
and human resource

00:54:25.270 --> 00:54:27.850
violation or difficulty
down the line as well.

00:54:27.850 --> 00:54:29.777
So yeah.

00:54:29.777 --> 00:54:30.610
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:54:30.610 --> 00:54:31.110
Cool.

00:54:33.787 --> 00:54:34.370
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:54:34.370 --> 00:54:35.932
Thanks for coming in.

00:54:35.932 --> 00:54:37.640
My wife and I are
actually in the process

00:54:37.640 --> 00:54:39.265
