00:54:39.265 --> 00:54:40.807
so this is true and
dear to my heart.

00:54:40.807 --> 00:54:41.973
KERRY MAGRO: That's awesome.

00:54:41.973 --> 00:54:43.200
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:54:43.200 --> 00:54:46.550
We just finished rounds
of performance reviews.

00:54:46.550 --> 00:54:51.770
And I'm curious to hear
what have you consulted

00:54:51.770 --> 00:54:53.480
various different
companies on how

00:54:53.480 --> 00:54:57.150
to provide effective feedback
for those who have autism

00:54:57.150 --> 00:55:02.600
in knowing their condition and
how to address and help them

00:55:02.600 --> 00:55:03.260
to grow?

00:55:03.260 --> 00:55:04.010
KERRY MAGRO: Sure.

00:55:04.010 --> 00:55:06.800
So a perfect example--

00:55:06.800 --> 00:55:10.250
so the companies we've spoken
to so far, and the bigger

00:55:10.250 --> 00:55:12.860
companies-- we've gone to many
small parent-run organizations.

00:55:12.860 --> 00:55:19.460
But we've been to PNC, American
Express, JP Morgan Chase, PSEG,

00:55:19.460 --> 00:55:20.360
Wyndham Worldwide.

00:55:20.360 --> 00:55:21.950
So we've even done
hotels and how

00:55:21.950 --> 00:55:26.900
to be friendlier to hotel guests
who might have individuals

00:55:26.900 --> 00:55:28.230
with disabilities.

00:55:28.230 --> 00:55:31.730
So one of the biggest
things we kind of talk about

00:55:31.730 --> 00:55:35.540
in that realm, about
trying to having

00:55:35.540 --> 00:55:38.090
that communication
and that feedback,

00:55:38.090 --> 00:55:42.620
is to truly kind of assess
short- and long-term goals

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:44.439
with all individuals.

00:55:44.439 --> 00:55:46.730
And this is not only for
individuals with disabilities,

00:55:46.730 --> 00:55:49.160
but we should be doing more
one-on-ones, whether it

00:55:49.160 --> 00:55:52.250
be on a weekly basis,
a bi-weekly basis,

00:55:52.250 --> 00:55:55.880
and trying to assess,
especially to disclose, just

00:55:55.880 --> 00:56:00.440
how their process is
going in a specific job

00:56:00.440 --> 00:56:04.370
and not necessarily
focus like, so Kerry,

00:56:04.370 --> 00:56:07.190
how are you doing as a person
with autism at this job?

00:56:07.190 --> 00:56:10.130
Just being just
one-on-one with them

00:56:10.130 --> 00:56:12.650
about if their
accommodations-- if they

00:56:12.650 --> 00:56:14.240
need more accommodations
once they've

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:15.440
actually disclosed that.

00:56:15.440 --> 00:56:18.000
I think that's one of the
biggest, biggest things.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:21.320
We need more communication
and open communication

00:56:21.320 --> 00:56:23.780
because a lot of these
people also think literally.

00:56:23.780 --> 00:56:27.860
They also don't
necessarily understand

00:56:27.860 --> 00:56:30.470
things such as different
tones of voice,

00:56:30.470 --> 00:56:32.270
different tones of
language, and especially

00:56:32.270 --> 00:56:33.936
when it comes to body
language and being

00:56:33.936 --> 00:56:36.800
able to understand facial
expressions and facial cues

00:56:36.800 --> 00:56:37.770
as well.

00:56:37.770 --> 00:56:39.590
So the more literal, the better.

